    "is_good_patch": true,
    "synth_pr": "\n## Title: Fix uninitialized mutex/condition variable usage in NFAPI sync\n\n### Summary\nThe `wait_nfapi_init()` function in multiple OAI executables was using uninitialized pthread mutex and condition variables (`nfapi_sync_mutex` and `nfapi_sync_cond`). This could lead to undefined behavior, including potential deadlocks or crashes when the synchronization primitives were accessed.\n\nThe variables were declared in the global scope but never initialized with `pthread_mutex_init()` and `pthread_cond_init()` before being used in the `wait_nfapi_init()` function.\n\n### Changes\n- `executables/lte-softmodem.c`: Added initialization of `nfapi_sync_mutex` and `nfapi_sync_cond` in the NFAPI-related initialization block\n- `executables/lte-uesoftmodem.c`: Added initialization and cleanup of `nfapi_sync_mutex` and `nfapi_sync_cond` \n- `executables/nr-softmodem.c`: Added initialization of `nfapi_sync_mutex` and `nfapi_sync_cond` in the NFAPI-related initialization block\n\n### Reproduction\nWhen running OAI in NFAPI mode (VNF or PNF), the `wait_nfapi_init()` function would be called during startup. Due to the uninitialized synchronization primitives, the behavior was undefined and could manifest as:\n- Deadlock during startup when waiting for NFAPI synchronization\n- Segmentation fault when trying to lock/unlock the uninitialized mutex\n- Incorrect synchronization allowing premature continuation before NFAPI connection was established\n\nThe issue was particularly noticeable in environments with varying timing or when NFAPI connections took longer to establish.\n"
}